    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Many scholars and critics argue that originalism is often used as a pretext to impose a conservative or libertarian agenda on the Constitution, rather than a genuine attempt to understand the framers' intentions. This criticism is rooted in the fact that many originalist scholars and judges selectively cherry-pick historical evidence, ignore or downplay the framers' views on certain issues, and impose their own modern values on the text. The Federalist Papers, for example, contain passages that contradict originalist interpretations, and many framers explicitly rejected the idea that the Constitution was a fixed, unchanging document. This has led some to view originalism as a tool for judicial activism, rather than a legitimate method of constitutional interpretation.",
